    <h2>
        Types of orange cats
    </h2>
    <p>
        <li>Tabby</li>
        <li>American Shorthair</li>
        <li>Cornish Rex</li>
        <li>British Shorthair</li>
        <li>American Curl</li>
    </p>
    <h2>
        Characteristics of orange cats
    </h2>
    <p>
        Orange cats are often described as friendly and affectionate. 
        They enjoy human companionship and are known for their cuddly nature, frequently seeking attention and affection from their owners. 
        These cats tend to be playful and energetic, enjoying interactive play and exploration. 
        Their curious nature makes them great companions for active households. 
        Orange cats are known for being vocal, often communicating through a range of sounds, including meows, purrs, and chirps. 
        This expressiveness can make them engaging pets.
        Despite their affectionate nature, orange cats also value their independence. 
        They can entertain themselves and are not overly clingy, making them suitable for owners with busy lifestyles. 
    </p>
    <h2>
        Physical attributes
    </h2>
    <p>
        Orange cats are typically tabbies, which means they have a coat pattern that includes stripes, spots, or swirls. 
        The most common patterns include mackerel (narrow stripes), classic (swirling patterns), and spotted. 
    </p>
    <h2>
        Should you get an orange cats?
    </h2>
    <p>
        In summary, orange cats are beloved for their striking appearance and engaging personalities. 
        They are generally friendly, playful, and affectionate, making them wonderful companions for many households.
    </p>
